          <div class="analysis-text">
            Sterling brings an elite wrestling pedigree from his bantamweight championship run — he's technically sound in the clinch, excellent at controlling the cage, and dangerous with his guillotine and neck cranks. Moving up to 145 lbs should give him more physical presence than at BW. However, his recent form has been inconsistent, and he enters this fight on a loss to Sean O'Malley.
            <br><br>
            Zalal has been on a tear. His submission of Josh Emmett — a former title challenger — in under two minutes at featherweight is significant. His BJJ at the elite level is genuinely dangerous, and he has the grappling credentials to match Sterling on the mat. The question is whether Sterling's more refined wrestling (takedowns, top control) beats Zalal's submission-oriented BJJ.
          </div>
